<GUIClass name="CnEcCalendarControl" id="51f26590-e465-485a-af73-41f3db488d39">
    <superclass name="BaseControl"/>
    <transient/>
    <sharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassSharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassTransientAllowed/>
    <transientAllowed/>
    <text>___________________________________________________________________________

              P R O P R I E T A R Y   N O T I C E

This software, in whole and in every part, is proprietary to Jade Software
Corporation Limited at Christchurch, New Zealand and is not to be
reproduced, used or disclosed except upon prior written permission of Jade
Software Corporation Limited.

  COPYRIGHT © JADE SOFTWARE CORPORATION LIMITED 2004 - ALL RIGHTS RESERVED
____________________________________________________________________________

This control provides the developer with a simple graphical calendar control, capable of
displaying any given month, with a variety of display options.

The control is resizable, both at design and runtime, and will redraw itself on command
via the resizeContents method.

As well as representing a month on the calendar graphically, the control also maintains an 
associated list of "calendar events", each with a date, a description, and an associated 
object.  the calendar control provides an interface to allow these events to be added to
the calendar, and inquired upon via date or associated object. 

When the month being shown by the calendar is changed, any events currently attached to 
the calendar occurring in the displayed month are shown (via their descriptions) on the
day they occur.


Methods
-------

Methods to control what is displayed

1. setDisplayMonth(month, year : Integer)
	Switch the calendar display to that month

2. incrementDisplayMonth(increment : Integer)
	Move calendar display forward (or backward) the number of months passed

3. setSelectedDate(date : Date, highlight : Boolean)
	Move the calendar display to the month including the date passed, set it as the 
	internal selected date, and highlight it if highlight is true

Methods to find out the control state

1. getDisplayMonth(month, year : Integer io)
	Return the month and year that are currently displayed

2. getSelectedDate() : Date
	Returns the date last clicked by the user (or null if there is none)

3. isDateVisible(date : Date)  : Boolean
	Returns true if the date passed is currently visible to the user (takes
	into account current showWeekends setting as well as current month)

Methods controlling physical appearance

1. repositionAfterResize()
	Standard JAS framework method to move and resize after a form resize event

2. resizeContents()
	Standard JAS framework method to repaint the control after its external 
	dimensions have been changed (eg. By JASSplitContainer)

3. setAvailableColor(color : Integer)
	Change the colour of current month days (will be actioned immediately).

4. setUnavailableColor(color : Integer)
	Change the colour of the filler days (will be actioned immediately).

5. setHighlightColor(color : Integer)
	Change the colour of highlighted days (will be actioned immediately).

6. setWeekStartsOn(day : Integer)
	Change the day on which the week starts (will redraw the calendar if required).

7. setShowWeekends(show : Boolean)
	Change whether or not the calendar is showing weekends (will redraw the calendar if required).

8. removeHighlights()
	Change any highlighted days back to the standard available colour

Methods to manage Calendar "Events"

1. createEvent(date : Date; display : String; obj :Object; highlight : Boolean) : Boolean
	Will create an event on the given date to the calendar, and display the text in the day 
	of the event if it occurs in the month currently being displayed.  If highlight is true, then the
	date where the event is created will be highlighted.  Will return false if add is unsuccessful.

2. deleteEventsForObject(obj : Object) : Boolean
	Will delete any existing events associated with the object passed, and redraw the current 
	month if necessary.  Will return false if no events are found.

3. deleteEventsForDate(date : Date) : Boolean
	Will delete any existing events occuring on the date specified, and redraw the current 
	month if necessary.  Will return false if no events are found.

4. getDatesForObject(obj : Object; dateArr : DateArray input)
	Will return an array of dates where events associated with the object passed exist.

5. getObjectsForDate(date : Date; coll : Collection input)
	Will return a collection of objects associated with events on the date given.

6. highlightDatesForObject(obj : Object) : Boolean
	Will find all events associated to the given object, switch the display to the month 
	of the first event, and highlight all the days where they occur.

7. clear()
	Reset the control to it's initial state - delete all the associated events, and clear
	all the highlights on the current month.

Design-Time Properties
----------------------

1. availableColor : Integer
	Colour of days in the current month, unhighlighted

2. unavailableColor : Integer
	Colour of day placeholders in prior and next month

3. highlightColor : Integer
	Colour of days which have been highlighted in the current month

4. headingColor : Integer
	Colour of the month and day headings

5. weekStartsOn : Integer
	Day to display in the leftmost column.  As per Jade Date::dayOfWeek 
	values (1 - Monday, 2- Tuesday, …, 7 - Sunday).

6. showWeekends : Boolean
	true to show weekend days, false otherwise

7. showMonthHeading : Boolean
	true to show the month name heading, false otherwise


Events
------

1. click - user has clicked on a day in the current month.

2. dblClick - user has "double-clicked" on a day in the current month.

3. monthChange - the display month on the calendar has changed for some reason</text>
